6 EXPERIMENTAL STUDY :
6-1:This experiment involves agents trying to escape from a burning building .
6-2:The environment is described as a spatial grid with a set of walls and (thankfully) some exits .
6-3:Time and space are considered discrete .
6-4:Time is divided in rounds .
6-5:Agents are localised by their position on the spatial grid .
6-6:These agents can move and communicate with other agents .
6-7:In a round, an agent can move of one cell in any of the four cardinal directions, provided it is not blocked by a wall .
6-8:In this application, agents communicate with any other agent (but, recall, a single one) given that this agent is in view, and that they have not yet exchanged their current favoured hypothesis .
6-9:Suddenly, a fire erupts in these premises .
6-10:From this moment, the fire propagates .
6-11:Each round, for each cases where there is fire, the fire propagates in the four directions .
6-12:However, the fire cannot propagate through a wall .
6-13:If the fire propagates in a case where an agent is positioned, that agent burns and is considered dead .
6-14:It can of course no longer move nor communicate .
6-15:If an agent gets to an exit, it is considered saved, and can no longer be burned .
6-16:Agents know the environment and the rules governing the dynamics of this environment, that is, they know the map as well as the rules of fire propagation previously described .
6-17:They also locally perceive this environment, but cannot see further than 3 cases away, in any direction .
6-18:Walls also block the line of view, preventing agents from seeing behind them .
6-19:Within their sight, they can see other agents and whether or not the cases they see are on fire .
6-20:All these perceptions are memorised .
