6-44:5.2 Experimental Settings The chosen experimental settings are the following: • Environmental topology Performances of information propagation are highly constrained by the environment topology .
6-45:The perception skills of the agents depend on the openness of the environment .
6-46:With a large number of walls the perceptions of agents are limited, and also the number of possible inter agent communications, whereas an open environment will provide optimal possibilities of perception and information propagation .
6-47:Thus, we propose a topological index (see below) as a common basis to charaterize the environments (maps) used during experimentations .
6-48:The topological index is the ratio of the number of cells that can be perceived by agents summed up from all possible positions, divided by the number of cells that would be perceived from the same positions but without any walls .
6-49:(The closer to 1, the more open the environment) .
6-50:We shall also use two additional, more classical [10], measures: the characteristic path length3 and the clustering coefficient4 .
