6-115:Efficiency of the Protocols The final experiment reported here is concerned with the analysis of the efficiency of the protocols .
6-116:We analysis here the mean size of the totality of the messages that are exchanged by agents (mean size of exchanges, for short) using the following protocols: HE, OE, and two variant protocols .
6-117:The first one is an intermediary restricted hypotheses exchange protocol .
6-118:RHE is as follows: it does not involve any challenge nor counter propose, which means that agents cannot switch their role during the protocol (this differs from RE in that respect) .
6-119:In short, RHE allows an agent to exhaust its partner"s criticism, and eventually this partner will come to adopt the agent"s hypothesis .
6-120:Note that this means that the autonomy of the agent is not preserved here (as an agent will essentially accept any hypothesis it cannot undermine), with the hope that the gain in efficiency will be significant enough to compensate a loss in effectiveness .
6-121:The second variant protocol is a complete observation exchange protocol .
6-122:COE uses the same principles as OE, but includes in addition all critical negative examples (nofire) in the exchange (thus giving all examples used as arguments by the hypotheses exchanges protocol), hence improving effectiveness .
6-123:Results for map 69 1 are shown on Fig .
6-124:5 .
6-125:Figure 5: Mean size of exchanges First we can observe the fact that the ordering of the protocols, from the least efficient to the most efficient, is COE, HE, RHE and then OE .
6-126:HE being more efficient than COE proves that the argumentation process gains efficiency by selecting when it is needed to provide negative example, which have less impact that positive ones in our specific testbed .
6-127:However, by communicating hypotheses before eventually giving observation to support it instead of directly giving the most crucial observations (OE), the argumentation process doubles the size of data exchanges .
6-128:It is the cost for ensuring consistency at the end of the exchange (a property that OE does not support) .
6-129:Also significant is the fact the the mean size of exchanges is slightly higher when the number of agents is small .
6-130:This is explained by the fact that in these cases only a very few agents have relevant informations in their possession, and that they will need to communicate a lot in order to come up with a common view of the situation .
6-131:When the number of agents increases, this knowledge is distributed over more agents which need shorter discussions to get to mutual consistency .
6-132:As a consequence, the relative gain in efficiency of using RHE appears to be better when the number of agents is small: when it is high, they will hardly argue anyway .
6-133:Finally, it is worth noticing that the standard deviation for these experiments is rather high, which means that the conversation do not converge to any stereotypic pattern. .
7-1:This paper has investigated the properties of a multiagent system where each (distributed) agent locally perceives its environment, and tries to reach consistency with other agents despite severe communication restrictions
7-2:In particular we have exhibited conditions allowing convergence, and experimentally investigated a typical situation where those conditions cannot hold
7-3:There are many possible extensions to this work, the first being to further investigate the properties of different global protocols belonging to the class we identified, and their influence on the outcome
7-4:There are in particular many heuristics, highly dependent on the context of the study, that could intuitively yield interesting results (in our study, selecting the recipient on the basis of what can be inferred from his observed actions could be such a heuristic)
7-5:One obvious candidate for longer term issues concern the relaxation of the assumption of perfect sensing.
